article.description: Chamique Holdsclaw scored 19 points, including two free throws with 19.2 seconds remaining, as the Washington Mystics held off the Miami Sol 65-60 Friday.
article.headline: Mystics grind out victory before sellout in Miami
article.linkText: Holdsclaw's brilliance keeps Mystics on track vs. Sol
article.story:
MIAMI (AP) -- Chamique Holdsclaw scored 19 points, including two free throws with 19.2 seconds remaining, as the Washington Mystics held off the Miami Sol 65-60 Friday. Miami had a chance to tie it with 13 seconds left, but Sheri Sam's 3-pointer from the left wing sailed off the back of the rim. Sam finished with 18 points for the Sol, who managed only three field goals in the final six minutes. "Our defense really, really pulled it out down the stretch,'' Holdsclaw said. "That's what has to happen on the road.'' Coco Miller made four free throws in the final 12.1 seconds for Washington, which improved its Eastern Conference-leading record to 8-2. Stacey Dales-Schuman added 11 points. "We took care of our business and didn't back down,'' Mystics coach Marianne Stanley said. "It was a huge statement on our part.'' The afternoon game was played in front of a sellout crowd of 10,412. Sandy Brondello, playing with a sprained and heavily bandaged left shoulder, led a late Miami charge. Brondello scored five points in a 40-second span, bringing the Sol within 59-58 with 1:01 remaining. But she misfired on a 15-footer with 24 seconds left, and Holdsclaw hit the clinching free throws seconds later. Miami fell to 1-4 in games decided by five points or less. "It's getting frustrating,'' Sam said, "We're going to keep losing games if we keep breaking down at the end.'' Washington took a 30-19 lead with 2:31 remaining in the first half after an 8-0 run. The Mystics then missed 14 of 17 shots, allowing Miami to go on a 20-8 run. It was capped by a Pollyanna Johns Kimbrough layup with 11:32 left that gave the Sol their first lead 39-38. Vanessa Nygaard connected on a 3-pointer with 8:07 remaining to give Miami its biggest edge 47-42. But the Sol was outscored 23-13 the rest of the way. Miller finished with 10 points for Washington, which scored 23 points off 17 Miami turnovers. "We didn't take care of the ball,'' Sol coach Ron Rothstein said. "We have had a lot of opportunities but aren't completing plays.'' Kimbrough had nine rebounds for Miami.

Game notes
Miami used its fifth different starting lineup in nine games. The Sol used only six lineups in the entire 2001 season. ... For the first time, the Sol lost consecutive regular-season games with Ruth Riley starting at center. ... Washington made four of its first five 3-point attempts in the game, then missed its final eight.
